<p class="p">Our primary interest is in the probability 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 </bold>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>
 </sub> = (
 <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 <sub class="sub">1,
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>
 </sub>, …, 
 <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 <sub class="sub">9,
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>
 </sub>), that is the probability of occurrence of each digit at year 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic>; we will refer to 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 </bold>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>
 </sub> as the 
 <italic class="italic">first-digit probability</italic>. More precisely, our target below will be on learning from the data about the dynamics governing the first-digit probability, 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 </bold>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">t</italic>
 </sub>, and on contrasting it with Benford’s Law, 
 <monospace class="monospace">p</monospace>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub>, in 
 <xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="pone.0213300.e001" class="xref">Eq (1)</xref>.
</p>
